<paper id="1952054005"><title>A Simple and Secure Way to Show the Validity of Your Public Key</title><year>1987</year><authors><author org="CENTRUM VOOR WISKUNDE EN INFORMATICA" id="2035113235">Jeroen van de Graaf</author><author org="Universidad Católica de Chile &gt;  &gt;  &gt;  &gt;" id="2148338499">René Peralta</author></authors><n_citation>72</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1529925669</reference><reference>1829613831</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48184-2_9</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46217">Integer</keyword><keyword weight="0.50886">Quadratic residue</keyword><keyword weight="0.46633">Chinese remainder theorem</keyword><keyword weight="0.4227">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.48893">Modulo</keyword><keyword weight="0.43294">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47782">Prime factor</keyword><keyword weight="0.51335">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.45307">Congruence (geometry)</keyword><keyword weight="0.59578">Universal composability</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present a protocol for convincing an opponent that an integer N is of the form PrQs, with P and Q primes congruent to 3 modulo 4 and with r and s odd. Our protocol is provably secure in the sense that it does not reveal the factors of N. The protocol is very fast and therefore can be used in practice.</abstract></paper>